Introduction

The purpose of this report is to analyze how six molecular variables are associated with levels of LC50. We are examining the fish toxicity data set which measures the concentration of chemicals that cause death in 50% of fathead minnows. The data set can be found at this link: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/QSAR+fish+toxicity

There are six descriptors in this data set and one response variable. First, MLOGP is a molecular property factor. Secondly, CIC0 contains complementary information content with neighborhood symmetry of 0 order. Moreover, GATS1i represents the geary autocorrelation of lag 1 weighted by ionization potential. Furthermore, NdssC and NdsCH are categrical variables that contain atom-type counts. SM1_Dz contains 2d matrix based descriptors and LC50 is the response which is the concentration that causes death in 50% of test fish over a test duration of 96 hours.

This report uses two packages. The first is the tidyverse package, a collection of R packages that are similar and designed to work together. The second package is GGally which is similar to ggplot2 but allows us to create more plots include the pairs plot.

library(tidyverse)
library(GGally)

In the last section of EDA a function is created to transform the values of a variable into “low” or “high” depending on whether the value is less than or equal to, or greater than the median of the variable.

newFishData <- fishData
funLowHigh <- function(column) {
  return(if_else(column <= median(column), "low", "high"))
}

This function is then applied to to every column in the fishData data set and the resulting data set is turned into a data frame.

newFishData <- apply(X = newFishData,
      MARGIN = 2,
      FUN = funLowHigh)
newFishData <- data.frame(newFishData)

Multiple linear regression

A model is created using GATS1i, NdsCH, and the interaction term of these two variables.

Subsequently, diagnostic plots are created to examine the model fit and normality assumptions.The fitted value vs residuals plot of LC50 and SM1_Dz displays a relatively random scatter and therefore the homoscedasticity assumption holds. This being said, points in the bottom right of the plot are worrisome so we may need to transform our model.

plot(fitSM1_Dz, which = 1)

The QQ plot displays a relatively straight line indicating the normality assumption is met.

plot(fitSM1_Dz, which = 2)

Finally, the fitSM1_Dz and fitNdsCH models created previously are used to predict the value of LC50. The values used are the median values of the variables in each model.

predict(fitSM1_Dz, newdata = data.frame(SM1_Dz = median(fishData$SM1_Dz)))
##        1 
## 4.076156
predict(fitNdsCH, newdata = data.frame(GATS1i = median(fishData$GATS1i), NdsCH = median(fishData$NdsCH)))
##        1 
## 3.972807
